Business Day

INVESTING WITH: William J. Nasgovitz And Eric J. Miller; Heartland Value Fund

By CAROLE GOULDJULY 20, 2003



Continue reading the main story
Share This Page

Continue reading the main story









THE bull is out of the barn, say William J. Nasgovitz and Eric J. Miller, co-managers of the $1.02 billion Heartland Value fund, which specializes in small companies.The managers point to various signs that a bull market began in April: rising corporate profits in 2002, historically low interest rates and technical trading patterns that suggested that a market bottom had been reached and that stocks were on the way up.The stocks of small companies are in their fourth year of outperforming bigger stocks. But small stocks ''are coming off an incredibly depressed valuation base after the speculative excesses'' of 1998 to 2000, Mr. Nasgovitz said from the managers' office in Milwaukee.Smaller companies are still much cheaper than big ones, Mr. Miller said. ''We're finding scores of small-cap and microcap companies that are industry leaders but selling at half the market multiple or less,'' he added.

Advertisement

Continue reading the main story

The fund returned 17.3 percent a year, on average, for the three years through Thursday, placing in the top 6 percent of funds that buy small-cap value stocks. That category gained 10.6 percent, annualized, compared with a loss of 12.1 percent for the Standard & Poor's 500-stock index, according to Morningstar Inc. Continue reading the main story







Advertisement

Continue reading the main story





The fund returned 27.3 percent in the last 12 months, compared with a gain of 13.5 percent for its group and a 10.3 percent loss for the S.& P. 500.Mr. Nasgovitz, 58, is the founder and president of Heartland Advisors, the fund's adviser. Mr. Miller, 49, is a senior vice president of the adviser. Heartland manages about $1.4 billion for institutions and individuals.The managers buy stocks with market capitalizations of less than $1.5 billion. About two-thirds of the stocks in the portfolio are microcaps, defined as having market caps of less than $300 million. Over all, the portfolio companies' median market capitalization is $151 million.Timing the purchase of a microcap stock is particularly tricky, Mr. Nasgovitz said. ''Because the companies have little or no analyst coverage,'' he said, ''they can be great stories but they may not get discovered until two years later.''To minimize these and other risks, the managers use traditional value measures, seeking companies with low ratios of price to earnings, price to book value and price to cash flow.They also want companies with relatively little debt, generally those with a ratio of debt to total capitalization of no more than 25 percent. That ratio now averages 20 percent for the portfolio, Mr. Miller said.Mr. Nasgovitz says microcap stocks have also been performing well because they have received more attention from hedge funds, which he called a ''growing and important side of the equity market.''

Advertisement

Continue reading the main story

The managers visit 500 to 1,000 companies a year, conducting what they call ''on the ground'' research.
