''We like to get a feel for what's going on in the trenches from the people who are doing the production and making the sales,'' Mr. Miller said.The managers start selling microcap stocks as they approach 85 to 90 percent of their price targets, and sell bigger companies as they reach their targets.Among the fund's holdings are shares of the Regis Corporation, the hair salon company whose brands include Regis, MasterCuts and Trade Secret. The fund originally bought shares in January 2001 and has paid $14.90, on average, for the entire position. The shares now trade at $29.45; the managers say they believe shares will be worth $34 in the next 12 to 18 months.Mr. Nasgovitz called Regis ''a low-risk retail play'' that has provided consistent and solid growth in same-store sales, those for salons open at least a year.Regis, which is based in Minneapolis, earned $1.59 a share in the 2002 fiscal year, compared with $1.26 a share the previous year.The managers began buying shares of Ribapharm Inc., a biotechnology company in Costa Mesa, Calif., in April 2002 at $7.79, on average. The stock now trades at $5.58, compared with a target price of $10.Ribapharm produces Ribaviran, which is used to treat hepatitis C. ICN Pharmaceuticals, which owns 80 percent of Ribapharm shares, spun off 20 percent of the company last year at $10 a share and is trying to repurchase those shares for $5.60.The fund, which has owned shares in ICN for years, acquired shares of Ribapharm in the spinoff..Last week, a federal judge in California ruled that three generic versions of Ribavarin did not infringe on Ribapharm's patents. The company plans to appeal that ruling.

Advertisement

Continue reading the main story

''Even if they lose that appeal, we believe Ribapharm should earn 40 cents a share next year, so it appears to us that the downside is already fully priced into the market,'' Mr. Nasgovitz said.THE fund originally bought shares of the Presidential Life Corporation, an insurer based in Nyack, N.Y., in September 1994, paying $6.06, on average. The stock now trades at $15.59, compared with the managers' target price of $20.The company recently wrote off some investments in high-yield telecommunications bonds, Mr. Nasgovitz said, but its tangible book value still exceeds $14 a share. He expects the company to earn $1.40 a share in 2004, up from the 90 cents a share projected for 2003.Company insiders have made more than 30 purchases so far this year, he added, and Herbert Kurz, the president and chairman, owns nearly 30 percent of the company. Continue reading the main story






